    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup cols="2">
      <title>
        Minimal Sums
      </title>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find two positive numbers whose product is <m>10 </m>, 
vand
            whose sum is a minimum. What is the minimum?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The two numbers are both <m>\sqrt{10}</m>, so the minimum sum is
            <m>\frac{2}{\sqrt{10}}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>
          Generalization 1
        </title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find two positive numbers whose product is <m>M</m>, and whose sum is a
            minimum. What is the minimum?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The two numbers are both <m>\sqrt{M}</m>, so the minimum sum is
            <m>\frac{2}{\sqrt{M}}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>
          Generalization 2
        </title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find two positive numbers whose product is <m>M</m>, and  the sum one
            number and three times the other  is a
            minimum. What is the minimum?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            One  number is <m>\sqrt{3M}</m>, and the other is
            <m>\sqrt{\frac{M}{3}}</m> so the minimum sum is
            <m>4\sqrt{\frac{M}{3}}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>
          Generalization 3
        </title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find two positive numbers whose product is <m>M</m>, and  the sum one
            number and <m>n</m> times the other  is a
            minimum. What is the minimum?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Nope. Figure this one out for yourself. There is a pattern in the
            previous problems.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>


    <exercisegroup cols="2">
      <title>
        Enclosures
      </title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          You have <m>500</m> meters of fencing with which to build a pen. 
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the largest area you can enclose with a freestanding rectangular
            pen?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>250^2/4</m> square feet
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>
          Generalization 1
        </title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            You want to build a large rectangular pen divided into two
            equally sized sub-pens. What is the largest area you can
            enclose?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>(250^2/6</m> square feet
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>
          Generalization 2
        </title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            You want to build a large rectangular pen divided into three
            equally sized sub-pens. What is the largest area you can
            enclose?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{250^2}{8}</m> square feet
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>
          Generalization 3
        </title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            You want to build a large rectangular pen divided into <m>n</m>
            equally sized sub-pens. What is the largest area you can
            enclose?

          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{250^2}{2(n+1)}</m> square feet. 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>
          Generalization 4
        </title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            You wish to build a pen using one side of a building in place of
            one side of your pen. What is the largest area you can enclose this
            time?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>250^2/2</m> square feet
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

